Rotten Tomatoes Lite

Minimalist Movie Exploration Experience: A case study of personalization

The merits of personalization would be appreciated only if it’s bundled with a good User Experience design. We iteratively redesigned a well-known and trusted movie rating site: Rotten Tomatoes with well-thought personalization feature, to reduce unnecessary cognitive workload.

Project Scope

Course Project for Introduction to HCI Methods

University of British Columbia

Rotten Tomatoes Lite is a 10 week long course project for Human Computer Interaction methods. It is a redesign of a crowdsourced movie rating and recommendation website Rotten Tomatoes. 

​

The target users of this project are whom with busy schedule but would love to enjoy some movie entertainment to best utilize their rest time. The prompt is to bring user-centered design to improve efficiency and experience of the movie exploration process. 

​

​

Process

What are users' goals and motivation? How do users interact with the current interface? 
What problems are we trying to solve? What are the requirements?
Iterations with conceptual models and prototypes, evaluated with cognitive walkthrough and usability testing.
Design
Recommendation

User Research

As a well-credited source of movie rating, Rotten Tomatoes has very valuable content, editors and audiences. However, when first open the site, one might have some comments. It can be on colour scheme, compact information or just unclear workflow. Which ones among them are the real problems to users? Which ones can be solved by User Experience design? We conducted an interface evaluation with current Rotten Tomatoes website.

Synthesis

Based on the user research result, we builded two personas that illustrate stakeholders' needs and characteristics.

Persona A

Emily, 27, movie lover

  • Has unique taste of movies

  • Enjoys going back to old movies, but they don’t always come to mind

  • Has more than one genres that she likes

  • Would like to share movies with friends who have similar taste

Persona B

  • Busy student with limited time 

  • Wants to relax when possible by watching movie

  • Wants to keep up with latest movie news

  • Would like to pre-order movie ticket upon decide on watching

Kevin, 22, college student

Requirements

Must Include:

  • Allow users to search for movies in a simple and easy way

  • Allow users to get a movie recommendation based on personal tastes

  • Clear synopsis

​

Should Include:

  • Allow users to keep track of preferred movies

  • Have a clear Tomatometer rating and information elements for each movie recommendation or movie search result

  • Allow users to reserve/purchase tickets on a specific date at a nearby theatre

​

Could Exclude:

  • Separated audience and editor Tomatometer ratings 

 

The main complaints about the current Rotten Tomatoes interface, based on our study, are its clutterness and lack of ticket reserving/purchasing capabilities. These requirements allow us to simplify the existing interface through excluding unnecessary information and personalization.

Prototype and iteration

Paper Prototype
Cognitive Walkthrough

We asked the user to go through an initial set up process that occurs after they log in for the first time.

​

  1. After setting their preferences, the user will then interact with the movies and set what movies they perhaps want to watch, love or dislike.

  2. They are further encouraged to do this based on the on-screen prompts that appear when they first use the homepage.

  3. They then go into the movie page to see a movie they showed interest in, and then the profile page to see how their preferences have already begun to affect their recommendations and movie suggestions.

​

Finding:

  • This conceptual design generally works well for users.

  • Flaws in the interface we noticed included confusions on interface elements and iconography, for example, the three icons under the movie titles on the homepage. Possible way to help with this problem is to add bubble prompts. 

  • We also noticed that when users use the buttons, like “Want to watch” when they start building their profile, they don’t understand the effect or value that this adds to their experience. 

Med-fidelity Prototype & Usability Testing

Extracting the strengths of both conceptual designs, we moved to the next stage of design: Mid-fidelity prototype. The prototype was implemented using Axure, with the goal to use minimum efforts and get most out of it.

 

Throughout the usability test, we asked the user to go through two tasks with think aloud techniques, followed by a short interview. Protocol:

​

  • Each participant was given a persona with a specific taste in movies. With the persona, we can predict which movie, director and genre users would add to their personal profile, and prepare recommendation pages in advance (Wizard-of-oz).

​

  • We started with participants assuming the role of first-time users who have just created their accounts on the personalized Rotten Tomatoes.  As they finish, they were asked two interview questions associated to how they feel this step contributes to the recommendations and what their expectation of recommendation page would be like.

​

  • Participants were asked to browse the movie recommendations on the homepage and movie information pages. Interview questions were directed at whether or not the recommendations corresponded to their expectation, whether the personalization was at the right level, and whether personalization buttons were helpful.

​

  • Participants were told that they can manage their preferences in their profile page. Their reactions and comments for the accumulated history and categories were recorded, and questions related to their subjective feelings of the profile management were asked.

​

​

Finding:

The presentation of the movie tiles on the homepage matched the users’ expectations for how the recommendations should be presented. After the users personalized their movies, they were positive with the idea of having the record of their actions kept on their profiles.

 

Although some users would like a few privacy toggles for some personalized movies, the general consensus was that the profile page itself was useful and worked as expected. While some of the processes associated with personalization could be more polished, the majority of users overall enjoyed the process of personalizing their experience with Rotten Tomatoes and the core metaphor of personalization worked well.

Design Recommendation

The setup matrix would have benefited from a tiered based system where options for each subcategory would appear based on what was chosen from the previous row. This would provide choices that the users might be familiar with. When we show actual recommendations, we should specify that they are shown in the order of relevance to their personalization, or allow them to choose a specific order.

 

For the recommendations, we should avoid showing movies that they tend to dislike, but also include some movies that may be outside of their specific preferences to encourage more discovery. The personalization buttons on the homepage should also be reduced to just an option for disliking, or going into the movie info page for more options. This allows the users to quickly specify whether they don’t like a movie, or they may be interested in it when they first glance at the poster. Then they can specify if they want to watch it, love it or dislike it when they get to that movie info page. This helps the users to avoid confusion with having too many options on the homepage.

 

The bubbles were important in helping the users to understand what each button means, but they neither visible nor dynamic enough to attract the users’ attention. In order to fix this, we would need to animate them and have them be removable once the users understand the prompt.

 

Having a record kept for all personalization is also an essential part of our design, but some users may have concerns over privacy of having all movies stored in a list with no visibility control. To solve this privacy issue, we could add a feature that hides specific movies and can be unhide if needed.
